recommandationVideos.Title: Decisions, overwhelmingly wrong
recommandationVideos.Description:
Direct link to parliament TV, https://parliamentlive.tv/Event/Index/5e1f14d2-72b3-488f-a53c-fc94fee92dac 

Link to Hansard full transcript, https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2024-01-16/debates/152B485D-812D-43CC-9D25-C2B651564810/ExcessDeathTrends?highlight=westminster hall#contribution-46059AFE-9A03-472B-9364-0BF972E2E7D8

Miriam Cates 
(Penistone and Stocksbridge) (Con) 
I will be brief, because it is clear that there is far more demand to speak in the debate than there is time. That shows that we absolutely need a longer debate; we need a debate on the Floor of the House, because it is not just Members present who want to speak, and members of the public have shown enormous interest.
I will not go over the excellent points that have been made and the data that has been shared. We know we have a problem in this country with excess deaths, particularly among younger people and particularly from cardiovascular disease. That, in itself, is a huge challenge. We need medical experts and statisticians to address those issues‚ÄîI am not qualified to do so.
What I will say is this: lockdown changed everything. Our response to covid changed everything. Just as we look back on different periods of history‚Äîbefore the war; before the industrial revolution‚ÄîI believe we will look back at before and after lockdown. Lockdown has changed our economy and how we relate to each other. It has changed our health and our understanding of children‚Äôs development.
The conditions under which those decisions were made‚Äîdecisions that were overwhelmingly wrong, in my opinion, although I do not blame any individuals, given the pressure they were under‚Äîhave not changed. The conditions under which we suspended the precautionary principle, ignored the fact that interventions may cause harm, suspended the importance of children‚Äôs education, suspended the safeguarding of children, suspended the need for medical trials and suspended all sorts of safeguards that have stood society in good stead for a long time have not changed.
The conditions in Government, the media and wider society under which those decisions were made have not changed because, unfortunately, we have not yet got to the heart of the matter. Why did that pressure come from the media? Why did we have to follow what other countries were doing? Why were we obsessed with particular points of data, such as deaths from covid, rather than considering the wider impact on society?
My concern about the covid inquiry is that it is asking all the wrong questions. It is concerned with who swore at whom on WhatsApp, and not the wider conditions under which decisions were made. When, several Education Secretaries ago, the former, former, former Secretary of State for Education, my right hon. Friend the Member for South Staffordshire (Sir Gavin Williamson), stood up in the House of Commons and said that he would close schools, I remember, as a mother, shouting at the television, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt do it! Don‚Äôt do it!‚Äù. I could see the impact it would have‚Äînot just on my own children, but across all the wider components of society. Society is like a big machine; we cannot just take out one part and assume that the rest will continue to operate. We have seen that clearly over the past three years.
We must address the reasons why these decisions were made. We cannot do that in three minutes each‚Äîwe must have a longer debate.

Mulle on tietysti helppoa puhua suomea, joten me p√§√§tettii ett√§ me ruvetaan tekem√§√§n n√§it√§ videoita yhess√§. Min√§ siis hoidan puhumisen ja suomenkieliset tekstit, ja mun poikayst√§v√§ lis√§√§ videoihin englanninkieliset k√§√§nn√∂kset sek√§ hoitaa editoinnin. Englanninkieliset tekstit ei oo aina t√§ysin luontevia, koska me pyrit√§√§n k√§√§nt√§m√§√§n mahollisimman paljo sanasta sanaan. Me toivotaan, ett√§ n√§ist√§ videoista ois hy√∂ty√§ muillekki suomen kielen opiskelijoille! Mun puheessa kuuluu se, ett√§ m√§√§ oon kotosin Oulun alueelta. Sen takia m√§√§ sanon esimerkiksi m√§√§ ja s√§√§ toisin kun vaikkapa helsinkil√§iset, jotka sanoo m√§ ja s√§. Monet muutki asiat m√§√§ sanon oululaisittain, koska se on mun luonnollinen puhetapa. Jos teill√§ tulee ideoita sen suhteen, mink√§laisista aiheista te haluaisitte kuulla mun puhuvan, niin kertokaa se kommenteissa!

ENGLISH

Hi again! I thought to tell a little bit more about where we got the idea to make these videos. I, who speak in these videos, am native Finnish and speak Finnish as my mother tongue. My boyfriend on the other hand is originally from Ireland, and he would very much like to learn Finnish. He says that from YouTube it is hard to find useful material for Finnish listening. The best material he has found from a channel called Finnished. There you can also find spoken Finnish that has been added subtitles in English and Finnish. My boyfriend has watched that channel‚Äôs all videos already so many times that he longs now for new material. To me it is of course easy to speak Finnish, so we decided that we‚Äôll start to make these videos together. So I take care of speaking and the Finnish texts, and my boyfriend adds to the videos English language translations and takes care of editing. The English texts are not always fully natural, because we aim to translate as much as possible word for word. We hope that these videos will be of use to other Finnish students as well! In my speaking you can hear the fact that I‚Äôm from Oulu region. That‚Äôs why I say, for example, m√§√§ and s√§√§ unlike, for instance, Helsinkians, who say m√§ and s√§. Also many other things I say the way they‚Äôre said in Oulu, because that‚Äôs my natural way of speaking. If you guys get ideas concerning what kind of topics you‚Äôd like to hear me talk about tell it in the comments!

** ABOUT THE CHANNEL **

The aim of this channel is to produce useful listening content in spoken Finnish, to help anyone who is learning the language. Most Finnish learning materials and courses emphasise the written form of Finnish (kirjakieli), which differs quite a lot from the spoken form (puhekieli).

We were inspired to start this channel by watching videos from the 'Finnished' YouTube channel. If you haven't checked out those videos yet, we recommend that you do! Our channel has a similar learning philosophy, based on Stephen Krashen's Input Hypothesis and a natural approach to language learning. We have also adopted the same approach for writing English subtitles. Namely, the English subtitles are not written in perfect English, instead they are more like a word-for-word translation of the Finnish text. This is intended to help the learner to better identify which Finnish and English words correspond to each another.

We hope you enjoy our videos, and if you have any suggestions for future topics, please let us know!

Note: The Finnish you hear spoken on this channel is in a mild Oulu dialect.

recommandationVideos.Title: Stefan Baumgartner - Trials, Traits, and Tribulations
recommandationVideos.Description:
We have all been there: The sprint‚Äôs closing, a deadline is about to arrive, and our feature needs to be shipped. Our best intentions are thrown overboard and we‚Äôre done when the compiler is happy with our work. Don‚Äôt panic! ‚Äì But let‚Äôs throw a little unwrap in there, what could go wrong? Famous last words.

Rinse and repeat, and you‚Äôll end up with winding, unwieldy functions, and kitchen sink structs, that past you wrote, but future you will have a hard time understanding. Let‚Äôs help ourselves, and all our colleagues, and refactor to something better. All we need to do is to remember some unique features of Rust, and implement the right traits for the right structs.

In this talk, we will refactor a single function with hundreds of lines of code together. We will learn to leverage expressions, define clear error boundaries, and implement standard library traits that align our code with Rust‚Äôs broader ecosystem. The result will be expressive, clear, and hopefully nothing else but beautiful.

recommandationVideos.Title: Noexcept? Enabling Testing of Contract Checks in C   - Pablo Halpern & Timur Doumler - CppCon 2023
Keywords: Testing of Contract Checks in C
testing of contract checks in cpp
recommandationVideos.Description:
https://cppcon.org/
---

Noexcept? Enabling Testing of Contract Checks in C   - Pablo Halpern & Timur Doumler - CppCon 2023
https://github.com/CppCon/CppCon2023

Should `noexcept` be part of your function's contract? A function's *contract* is the set of pre-conditions promised by the the caller and the set of post-conditions promised by the function itself, including whether or not it throws an exception. Naively, then, it would seem that `noexcept` is a good way to indicate that your function does not throw when called in contract, but things are not so simple. In this talk, we'll review the original purpose of the `noexcept` specifier and the `noexcept` operator. We'll look at how runtime contract checks can be tested and how `noexcept` interferes with such testing. Along the way, we'll touch on the proposed contract-checking feature in C  26, eventually arriving at an alternative exception-specification annotation that would mesh far better with contract checking than `noexcept` currently does.
---

Timur Doumler

Timur Doumler is the co-host of CppCast and an active member of the ISO C   standard committee, where he is currently co-chair of SG21, the Contracts study group. Timur started his journey into C   in computational astrophysics, where he was working on cosmological simulations. He then moved into the audio and music technology industry, where he has been working for over a decade and co-founded the music tech startup Cradle. In the past, Timur also worked for JetBrains, first as a developer on CLion's C   parser and later as a Developer Advocate for C   developer tools. Currently, Timur lives in Finland, where he is organising the monthly C   Helsinki meetup. Timur is passionate about clean code, good tools, low latency, and the evolution of the C   language.
---

Pablo Halpern

Pablo Halpern is a freelance software developer and consultant. He has been programming in C   since 1989 and has been a member of the C   Standards Committee since 2007. His main contributions to the C   Standard has been in the area of parallel and vector programming, and he is largely responsible for taking allocators from a curiosity in C  03 to a usable feature of the Standard Library in C  11 and beyond. He continues to work on language and library features to make allocator use simpler and less error prone. Pablo is the author of The C   Standard Library from Scratch (Que, 2000), and is a major contributor to Embracing Modern C   Safely (Pearson, 2021). He has given talks on a number of topics at the CppCon and ACCU conferences. Pablo lives with his partner in Boston, MA. When not working on books and allocators, he enjoys travel, model rocketry, biking, hiking, skiing, snowboarding, and watching opera.
---

resultVideos.Title: Towards a more diverse and inclusive society: Discussing Racism and Discrimination in Oulu
resultVideos.Description:
A diverse panel of experts, including a researcher of racism, a member of the public administration of Oulu, and an NGO representative discuss experiences of racism and discrimination in Oulu. The panel aims to pinpoint what challenges the inclusion of marginalized groups into our society. The panel will be held in English. 

This event is organized as a part of the UNIC CityLabs event series. UNIC is an alliance of eight European universities. In the UNIC CityLabs, students, researchers and citizens are empowered to identify the societal challenges of post-industrial cities, co-create solutions to these challenges, and implement the solutions locally. 

Panelists include: Boby Mafi, teacher and researcher in Education and Globalisation at the University of Oulu, Jamal Awad, Interpreter and Head of the Oulu Migrant council, Ahed Hussein, Development Manager at Startup Refugees. The discussion will be hosted by graduate student of Education and Globalisation Junko Tanaka.

The occasion is part of the activities of the university pop-up space: https://www.oulu.fi/yliopisto/popup‚Äã.
resultVideos.Author: University of Oulu
